					<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Frustum of cone is the part of co=
ne when it is cut by a plane into two parts. The upper part of cone remains=
 same in shape but the bottom part makes a frustum. To get this part of the=
 </span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">right circular cone</span><span s=
tyle=3D"font-weight: 400;"> we have to slice it horizontally or parallel to=
 the base. Both pieces have different volumes and areas. Learn </span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://byjus.com/maths/volume-of-cone/"><span style=3D"font-weight: =
400;">Volume Of Cone</span></a><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> here.</sp=
an></p>
<p><img class=3D"alignnone" src=3D"https://cdn1.byjus.com/wp-content/upload=
s/2020/06/Frustum-Of-A-Cone-2.png" alt=3D"Frustum of Cone 1" width=3D"750" =
height=3D"350"></p>
<p>Frustum is a Latin word which means =E2=80=98piece cut off=E2=80=99. Whe=
n a solid (generally a cone or a pyramid) is cut in such a manner that base=
 of the solid and the plane cutting the solid are parallel to each other, p=
art of solid which remains between the parallel cutting plane and the base =
is known as frustum of that solid.</p>
<p>To visualize a frustum properly, consider an ice-cream cone which is com=
pletely filled with ice-cream. When the cone is cut in a manner as shown in=
 the figure, the section left between the base and parallel plane is the fr=
ustum of a cone.</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" class=3D"alignnone" src=3D"https://cdn1.byjus.com/=
wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Frustum-Of-A-Cone-1.png" alt=3D"Frustum of Cone =
2" width=3D"750" height=3D"350"></p>
<h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Volume of Frustum Cone</span></h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Let us learn here how to find the volu=
me of frustum of a cone with the help of diagram given. This formula will a=
lso help to find the volume of frustum of a pyramid which is shaped in the =
form of cone.</span></p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" class=3D"alignnone" src=3D"https://cdn1.byjus.com/=
wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Frustum-Of-A-Cone-3.png" alt=3D"Frustum of Cone =
3" width=3D"750" height=3D"512"></p>
<p>In the cone given above, the frustum can be considered as the difference=
 of two right circular cones.</p>
<p>Let the larger cone which has a height equal to =E2=80=9C<span class=3D"=
latex-for-amp">h=E2=80=9D</span> units, slant height as <span class=3D"late=
x-for-amp">=E2=80=9Cl=E2=80=9D</span> units and radius as <span class=3D"la=
tex-for-amp">=E2=80=9Cr=E2=80=9D</span>&nbsp;units be named as cone 1 and t=
he smaller right circular cone be named as cone 2 whose height is given as =
<span class=3D"latex-for-amp">h=E2=80=99</span> units, radius as <span clas=
s=3D"latex-for-amp">r=E2=80=99</span> units and the slant height as <span c=
lass=3D"latex-for-amp">l=E2=80=99</span> units.</p>
<p>The height of frustum is=E2=80=9DH=E2=80=9D units and its slant height i=
s =E2=80=9CL=E2=80=9D units.</p>
<div class=3D"mathjax-scroll">\(\begin{array}{l}The\ volume\ of\ right\ cir=
cular\ cone\ 1 =3D \frac{1}{3}~ \pi r^{2} h\end{array} \)</div>
<p>Similarly,</p>
<div class=3D"mathjax-scroll">\(\begin{array}{l}The\ volume\ of\ right\ cir=
cular\ cone\ 2 =3D \frac{1}{3}~ \pi r=E2=80=99^2 h'\end{array} \)</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Therefore, the volume of the frustum of cone can be given as:</p>
<div class=3D"mathjax-scroll">\(\begin{array}{l}Volume\ of\ frustum\ of\ co=
ne\ V =3D \frac{1}{3}~ \pi r^2~ h~-~\frac{1}{3}~ \pi r=E2=80=99^2 h'\end{ar=
ray} \)</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class=3D"mathjax-scroll">\(\begin{array}{l}Volume\ of\ frustum,\ V =3D=
 \frac{1}{3}~ \pi (r^2 ~h~-~r=E2=80=99^2 h=E2=80=99) =E2=80=A6(1)\end{array=
} \)</div>
<p>From the figure given above, in the <span class=3D"latex-for-amp">=E2=88=
=86OO=E2=80=99D </span>and <span class=3D"latex-for-amp">=E2=88=86OPB</span=
>;</p>
<p><span class=3D"latex-for-amp">=E2=88=A0DOO=E2=80=99</span>=3D <span clas=
s=3D"latex-for-amp">=E2=88=A0BOP</span>(<em>Common Angle</em>)</p>
<div class=3D"mathjax-scroll">\(\begin{array}{l}As\ \overleftrightarrow{CD}=
||\overleftrightarrow{AB}\ (Plane\ dividing\ the\ cone\ is\ parallel\ to\ t=
he\ base)\end{array} \)</div>
